messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path:
- /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas

HTTP methods (for that path) â€” based on the source code:

- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false

Explanation:
- The controller defines an explicit @RequestMapping on the method getConsumerPrintingSchemas:
  - @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas", method = RequestMethod.GET)
  This sets the full path to /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas and enables GET for that path.
- There is also a method mapped to the same path for POST:
  - @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas", method = RequestMethod.POST)
  This enables POST on the same path.
- Other mappings in this class (DELETE and PUT) include an extra path segment {printingSchemaID}:
  - @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}", method = RequestMethod.DELETE)
  - @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}", method = RequestMethod.PUT)
  Those do not apply to the path /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas (they apply only when the printingSchemaID path parameter is present).
- No @RequestMapping without a method attribute is present, and no explicit mappings for HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PUT, DELETE, PATCH exist for /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas. Following the instruction to base conclusions on the code (not on framework defaults/behavior), only GET and POST are considered acceptable for this exact path.
